ML1 : Insurance - case study¶

Classification¶

Author: Paula Gwanchele

The project is about building a model explaining travel insurance claim outcomes based on the training sample and generate predictions for all observations from the test sample.

2. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Initial exploration: Dataset description

The dataset includes travel insurance policy records with the following 14 columns:

  • reward – Commission value earned on the insurance sale
  • claim_status – Target variable (0 = Not Approved, 1 = Approved) Only in training sample
  • person_gender – Gender identifier of the insured person
  • entity_type – Type of selling entity
  • channel – Distribution channel used
  • support_interactions – Number of customer service interactions
  • agent_id – Identifier for the selling agent
  • customer_score – Computed value between 0-1 based on customer metrics
  • entity_a – Identifier of the agency that sold the policy
  • person_age – Age of the insured person
  • location – Destination of the trip
  • revenue – Net sales value of the policy (when <0 it covers discounts)
  • product_id – Name of the insurance product
  • trip_length – Duration of the insured trip in days

A broad overview: The types of data, shape and content¶

🔍 Column-by-Column Insights:¶

  • reward:

    • Represents the commission earned on the sale.
    • Mean = 9.79, but 25%, 50% percentiles are all 0, suggesting many zero values.
    • Max = 282.07, indicating a long right tail (heavily skewed).
    • Action: log transformation or normalization to handle skewness.

  • claim_status (Target Variable):

    • Mean = 0.0146 → only ~1.5% of claims are approved.
    • Indicates extreme class imbalance.
    • This leads to the use of balanced accuracy and consideration of class weighting or resampling techniques during modeling.

  • support_interactions:

    • Ranges from 0 to 6; Mean ≈ 1.09.
    • May be useful if more support = higher claim approval.
    • Action: To include in modeling, possibly there is a need to scale for some algorithms (e.g., KNN, SVM).

  • customer_score:

    • Ranges from 0 to 1, Mean ≈ 0.19.
    • Appears reasonably distributed but slightly right-skewed.

  • person_age:

    • Range: 18 to 100 years; Mean ≈ 39.7.
    • Most ages lie between 34–44 (25th to 75th percentile).
    • Action: Could bin into age groups (e.g., young, adult, senior) or keep continuous.

  • revenue:

    • Huge range: -406.6 to 801.0.
    • Negative values represent discounts.
    • Highly skewed and might affect models.
    • Action: to apply log or capped transformation.

  • trip_length:

    • Most trips are between 9 to 53 days, but max is 4856 days (~13 years!).
    • Likely contains data entry errors or outliers.
    • Action: To Cap extreme values or treat as outliers.

Interpretation;¶

from the countplot: The dataset is heavily imbalanced, with less than 2% approved claims. This makes balanced accuracy a more appropriate evaluation metric.
from the boxplot: Approved claims tend to have higher rewards, while non-approved ones often have zero. This suggests reward could be a useful predictor, but due to its skewed distribution, we engineered a binary feature reward_given to better capture this signal.

# Chi-Square Test for Categorical Features to assess corr with the target variable
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

print("Chi-Square Test Results for Categorical Features vs claim_status:\n")

categorical_features = ['person_gender', 'entity_type', 'channel', 'location', 'product_id']

for feature in categorical_features:
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(train_df[feature], train_df['claim_status'])
    chi2, p, dof, ex = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
    print(f"{feature}: chi2 = {chi2:.2f}, p-value = {p:.4f}")
    if p < 0.05:
        print("  → Significant relationship with claim_status\n")
    else:
        print("  → No significant relationship with claim_status\n")

Key Takeaways¶

  • Among all numeric features, revenue is the most promising predictor of claim approval.

  • Other features like reward and trip_length may offer weak but helpful signals.

  • support_interactions and person_age are likely not helpful for prediction and could be dropped or de-prioritized.

  • customer_score shows a slight positive trend — better scoring customers are a little more likely to be approved.

  • Pearson, Spearman, and Kendall results agree closely, giving confidence in these conclusions.

3. Feature Engineering¶

3.1 Handle Skewness & Outliers

In [36]:
# Cap trip_length at 99th percentile
trip_cap = train_df['trip_length'].quantile(0.99)
train_df['trip_length'] = np.where(train_df['trip_length'] > trip_cap, trip_cap, train_df['trip_length'])

# Log transform revenue (offset to avoid negative/0)
train_df['log_revenue'] = np.log1p(train_df['revenue'] - train_df['revenue'].min() + 1)

# Binary feature: was a reward given this helps with removing the 50% of the zeros 
train_df['reward_given'] = (train_df['reward'] > 0).astype(int)

# I need to fix for test_df as well
trip_cap = train_df['trip_length'].quantile(0.99)
test_df['trip_length'] = np.where(test_df['trip_length'] > trip_cap, trip_cap, test_df['trip_length'])

# Create binary reward feature
test_df['reward_given'] = (test_df['reward'] > 0).astype(int)

# Log transform revenue using same offset
revenue_offset = train_df['revenue'].min()
test_df['log_revenue'] = np.log1p(test_df['revenue'] - revenue_offset + 1)

Data Splitting¶

Use internal split to properly assess model performance. 1st split;
X_train = 60%
X_temp (which becomes validation + test) = 40%

2nd split;
X_val = 20%
X_test = 20%

5. Model Evaluation¶

Use balanced accuracy for all comparisons.

In [56]:
from sklearn.metrics import balanced_accuracy_score

models = {'Logistic Regression': log_model, 'KNN': knn, 'SVM': svm_model}
for name, model in models.items():
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)
    score = balanced_accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f'{name}: Balanced Accuracy = {score:.4f}')

Logistic Regression: Balanced Accuracy = 0.7305
KNN: Balanced Accuracy = 0.4998
SVM: Balanced Accuracy = 0.7450

🧠 Interpretation:¶

  • Balanced Accuracy = average of recall for each class (approved vs not approved). My dataset is imbalanced, so accuracy alone would be misleading.
  • I compared Logistic Regression, KNN, and SVM using balanced accuracy. SVM performed the best with a score of 0.7450, followed closely by Logistic Regression at 0.7305. KNN performed poorly (0.4998), likely due to the high dimensionality and class imbalance. We selected SVM as my final model for predictions on this 1st round.”

Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE)¶

I used this to identify the most impactful features.
RFE is a wrapper method that recursively removes the least important features and keeps the top ones.

In [66]:
